\begin_layout Section
Computer simulations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:MD"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computer simulations have evolved over the last decades to be one of the
 major tools for understanding how our world works.
 In the context of molecular simulations, before simulations it was only
 possible to extrapolate the time evolution of systems from a series of
 static states that were difficult to be obtained through various experimental
 methods (X-ray, NMR etc) simulations enable us to observe dynamical behaviour
 of systems at an atomistic or even Quantum Mechanical (QM) level.
 A broad set of different techniques are available to study dynamical behaviour
 of complex biological or chemical systems (as for example molecules) on
 the computer .
 Depending on the purpose and system parameters (system size, process time,
 process type) different simulation methods of various precisions are available.
 While for systems containing only tens of atoms, QM simulations over small
 timescales (arounds 1 ps) are possible, but going to a larger number of
 particles or longer timescales is not feasible using QM simulations.
 Hence simulation methods like classical molecular dynamics (MD) simulations
 which use simplified representations of the particle in the systems under
 study have to be used.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

For the purpose of this thesis, classical (MD) simulations was the appropriate
 choice since it fulfilled the constraints given by the system size (around
 200k atoms), time scales (50 ns to 100 ns) and processes studied (ligand
 molecule interactions).
 In this chapter a brief introduction into the theory behind MD simulations
 will be given.
 For a more in depth insight to the field of simulations the author would
 like to refer to additional literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Andrew,M.P.Allen1989,FrenkelDaan;Smit1996"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Potential energy surface and phase space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to study the function and behaviour of chemical systems, based
 on the dynamics of the atoms, classical MD simulation is used to explore
 the relevant areas of the systems potential energy surface (PES).
 The classical approach is based on the Born-Oppenheimer approximation,
 in which the movement of the electrons is separated from the nucleus due
 to the nucleus having a much higher mass.
 Considering this mass difference, the electrons are assumed to almost instantan
eously adjust their positions according to the position of the nucleus and
 their motion can therefore be negelected.
 The PES therefore is a 3N-6 
\lang british
dimensional
\lang english
 energy surface (hyper-surface) where each point represents the potential
 energy of a unique configuration of the system and the configurations are
 determined by the coordinates of each nuclei within the system.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:pes"

\end_inset

 such a hyper-surface is shown and since every point represents the energy
 of a given configuration of atoms, minima and maxima can be related to
 properties of that configuration.
 A local minimum for example represents a stable configuration of the system
 and usually the system moves within one well of its surface or depending
 on the well depth it can cross over between different minimum configurations.
 In order to map this hyper-surface either molecular mechanics (MM).
 In order to sample the required configurations needed to observe the dynamical
 behaviour of a system empirical force-fields (also referred to as MM) are
 used.
 Those force-fields describe the interaction of atoms as points that are
 interacting with each other over forces derived from an potential energy
 function.
 This potential energy function is built from parameterised additive potentials
 that are based on experimental or quantum mechanical data and only dependent
 on the nuclear coordinates.
 
