In classical MD simulations, the potential energy function derivative, in
 combination with Newton's equation of motion are used to sample the PES.
 By deriving the force on each particle from the potential energy function
 and integrating Newton's second equation of motion, new position and velocities
 of the atoms in our system can be calculated based on their current positions
 and velocity.
 By doing this MD simulations sample the phase space in which the state
 of a system is described by the position and velocities of each particle
 making the phase space a 6N dimensional space.
 Knowing the positions and velocities of each atom at a point in time, the
 potential energy at that time can be calculated, hence sampling the phase
 space automatically samples the PES.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integration Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the classical approximation the particles in the systems under study
 are described as point particles which move under the influence of a continuous
 potential.
 As previously mentioned, Newton's equation of motion needs to be integrated
 to obtain a new point within the phase space.
 To be able to integrate those equations, a finite difference technique
 (complex many body problems can not be solvent analytically) is used that
 breaks down the integration process into small stages, separated by a distincti
ve time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

.
 The size of this time-step in MD simulations is non trivial and therefore
 will be elaborated in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:timestep"

\end_inset

.
 Within one time-step the forces on each particle are assumed to be constant
 and are calculated as a sum of interactions with the other particles in
 the system.
 The force on each particle can be derived from the force-field that is
 used in the simulation (by taking the negative derivative of the potential
 energy function
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\delta V\,(r)}{\delta r}=F\,(r)$
\end_inset

) and from the force we ultimately obtain the acceleration and velocities
 of the particles giving us the new positions at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\delta t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

There are several integration schemes available to integrate the equations
 of motion using finite difference methods.
 Here, the basic integration scheme along with one variation will be outlined.
 All algorithms used for integration should hold the following properties:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Itemize
it should be time reversible
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
stable; i.e.
 energy conservation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
propagation through the phase space has to be computational, efficient (long
 enough time-steps 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

All integration algorithms assume that the position and dynamic properties
 can be represented as a Taylor series expansion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
r\,(t+\delta t) & = & r\,(t)+v\,(t)*\delta t+\frac{1}{2}a\,(t)*\delta t^{2}+\ldots\\
v\,(t+\delta t) & = & v\,(t_{0})+a\,(t_{0})*\delta t+\frac{1}{2}b\,(t)v\delta t^{2}+\ldots\\
a\,(t+\delta t) & = & a\,(t)+b\,(t)*\delta t+\frac{1}{2}c\,(t)*\delta t^{2}+\ldots
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

One of the first and most widely used integration methods is the Verlet
 algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Swope1982"

\end_inset

 which uses the positions of the previous time-step along with the current
 positions to calculate the new positions at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\delta$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
r\,(t+\delta t) & = & r\,(t)+v\,(t)\star\delta t+\frac{1}{2}\frac{F\,(t)}{m}\star\delta t^{2}+\ldots\\
r\,(t-\delta t) & = & r\,(t)-v\,(t)\star\delta t+\frac{1}{2}\frac{F\,(t)}{m}\star\delta t^{2}+\ldots
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

if we combine 1 and 2:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
r\,(t+\delta t) & = & 2r\,(t)-r\,(t-\delta t)+\frac{F\,(t)}{m}\star\delta t^{2}+\ldots
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

One disadvantage of the Verlet integration algorithm is that the velocities
 are not calculated explicitly during the integration process and thus have
 to be calculated separately.
 This is necessary since the velocity is needed to ensure energy conservation
 and to calculate further properties like the temperature of the system.
 Therefore variations of the Verlet algorithm that allow the explicit calculatio
n of the velocity have been sought.
 One of them being the Leap-frog algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hockney1974"

\end_inset

 that is outlined hereafter:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
v\,(t+\frac{1}{2}\delta t & )= & v\,\left(t-\frac{1}{2}\delta t\right)+a\,(t)\star\delta t\\
r\,(t+\delta t) & = & r\,(t)+v\,(t+\frac{1}{2}\delta t)\star\delta t
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The leap-frog algorithm that will be used throughout this thesis, uses the
 velocities from 
\begin_inset Formula $t-\frac{1}{2}\delta t$
\end_inset

 and the acceleration at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in order to calculate the velocities at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\frac{1}{2}\delta t$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain the new positions at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\delta t$
\end_inset

 the previously calculated velocities at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\frac{1}{2}\delta t$
\end_inset

 and the positions at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are used.
 The advantage of the leap-frog algorithm is that it explicitly includes
 the velocity but since the position and the velocities are not synchronised,
 the kinetic energy contribution can only be averaged at the time when the
 positions are calculated: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
v\,(t) & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[v\left(t-\frac{1}{2}\delta t\right)+v\left(t+\frac{1}{2}\delta t\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further integration schemes include the velocity verlet 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Swope1982"

\end_inset

 and the beeman algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Beeman1976"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Choice of Integration time-steps
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:timestep"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described previously in finite difference methods, choosing the correct
 time-step in which the total force on each particle is assumed to be constant
 is not trivial.
 The use of a large time step can result in instability of the system and
 a characteristic ¨explosion¨ an MD system due to high energies of overlapping
 atoms.
 On the other hand, time-steps that are chosen too small result in limited
 sampling of the phase space and hence will not reveal enough information
 about the behaviour of the system.
 In order to satisfy both requirements in MD simulations the time-step should
 be smaller then the highest frequency vibration of the system, which in
 the case of classical MD are the covalent bond to hydrogens stretching
 vibrations.
 Those vibrations are around 10 fs limiting the time-step in MD to around
 1 fs.
 In cases where the vibrations of hydrogen bonds are not essential for the
 dynamics of the system it is possible to increase the time-step by artificially
 constraining those vibrational movements.
 Two constraint algorithms which are used within this work are SHAKE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ryckaert1977"

\end_inset

 and LINCS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HessB;BekkerHBerendsenHJC"

\end_inset

 thus the time-step can be increased to 2 fs and have been used throughout
 this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Periodic Boundary Conditions (PBC)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:pbc"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When performing MD simulations the protein of interest is usually solvated
 within a simulation box.
 If using hard boundaries (i.e.
 a box with walls) surface effects would have a large undesirable effect
 on the dynamics of the system.
 In order to negatet these surface effects and preserving the dimensions
 of the simulation box along with keeping the number of particles constant,
 Periodic Boundary Conditions (PBC) are applied.
 In a PBC treated simulation the central simulation box is surrounded by
 images of itself where each atom in a replicated box moves according to
 its original particle in the central box.
 Therefore, if a particle crosses from one box to another, a mirror particle
 from a neighboring box enters the system thus preserving the number of
 particles.
 
\end_layout

