\begin_layout Subsection
Starting conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The success of an MD simulation is vastly dependent on the initial conformation
 of the system, hence care should be taken when choosing this conformation.
 These states can be generated using energy minimasation and equilibration
 of structures obtained from high-resolution structure data from X-ray or
 NMR.
 Besides the choice of the initial configuration, the assignment of the
 starting velocities for the system has to be done.
 One way to assign the initial velocities is by randomly choosing velocities
 from the Maxwell distribution that describes the probability of atom i
 with mass m having the velocity v at the desired system temperature T:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p\,(v_{ix}) & = & \left(\frac{m_{i}}{2\pi k_{B}T}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}exp\,\left[-\frac{1}{2}\frac{m_{i}v_{ix}^{2}}{k_{B}T}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the Boltzmann constant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Force Fields (Molecular Mechanics)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:MM"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described above, molecular mechanic force-fields are used to calculate
 the forces on each particle in the system.
 The potential energy function contains a set of additive potentials that
 describe inter and intra molecular interactions on each particle in the
 system.
 These potentials incorporate parameters that are usually obtained through
 experimental or quantum mechanical data and therefore are using information
 from known structures and their behaviour is used to try to predict the
 behaviour of unknown systems.
 There is no correct or true force-field which can be used for every purpose
 at the moment, but a number of force-fields which perform better in different
 tasks.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The GROMACS simulation package (in version 4.5.4) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Berendsen1995"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VanDerSpoel2005"

\end_inset

supports a series of different versions of AMBER
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cornell1995"

\end_inset

, CHARMM
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Guvench2011"

\end_inset

, GROMOS
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Oostenbrink2004"

\end_inset

 force-fields along with the OPLS force-field
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kaminski2001"

\end_inset

.
 In specific situation the system under study may require the use of polarisable
 force-fields.
 The different potentials in a simple force field can be separated in bonded
 and non-bonded potentials and will be described briefly.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{total} & = & V_{bonded}+V_{non-bonded}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bonded Potentials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The bonded part of the potential energy function in its simplest form can
 be written as followed.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{bonded} & = & \sum_{bond\, length}\nicefrac{1}{2}K_{b}(b-b_{0})^{2}+\sum_{bond\, angle}\nicefrac{1}{2}K_{\theta}(\theta-\theta_{0})^{2}+\\
 &  & \sum_{improper\, torsion}\nicefrac{1}{2}K_{\omega}(\omega-\omega_{0})^{2}+\sum_{proper\, torsion}\nicefrac{1}{2}K_{n}[1+cos\,(n\upsilon-\upsilon_{0})]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The three energy contributions that are modelled by harmonic potentials
 are the bond length, bond angle and the improper dihedral angles.
 In all three cases the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 describe the equilibrium length or angle while 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{b}/K_{\theta}/K_{\omega}$
\end_inset

 are the force constants obtained from other data.
 This simple description is in special cases (where certain system properties
 have to be described in more detail) not sufficient in order to get the
 desired accuracy, hence in all potentials additional or higher order terms
 can significantly improve the accuracy.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In case of the bond length, improvement can be achieved by using the Morse
 potential
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Morse1929"

\end_inset

, which addresses the fact that it is harder to compress a bond than to
 relax it.
 The Morse potential therefore improves the accurate description of the
 bond length energy from 0.3 Å up till 0.8 Å.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Also adding higher order terms to the harmonic potential describing the
 bond angle improves the accurate description from 30º up to 70º.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $V\,(\theta)=\frac{k_{\theta}}{2}(\theta-\theta_{0})^{2}\,[1-k_{\theta}^{\text{´}}(\theta-\theta_{0})-k_{\theta}^{\text{´´}}(\theta-\theta_{0})^{2}-k_{\theta}^{\text{´´´}}(\theta-\theta_{0})^{3}\ldots]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The more than two fold improvement in both cases is computationally expensive
 and therefore usually other methods for the improvement of accuracy are
 sought.
 The incorporation of computationally expensive methods as described above
 is depends on the performed study and system and in case of this thesis
 the basic terms were sufficient.
 In the case of the CHARMM forcefield, the Urey-Bradley term is added to
 the bond angle potential.This effectivly adds an harmonic potential to the
 1,3 atoms that exist in an angle term.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\,(\theta) & = & \sum\nicefrac{1}{2}K_{\theta}(\theta-\theta_{0})^{2}+k_{UB}(r_{i}-r_{0})^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The final term described by a harmonic potential is the improper dihedral
 angle term that restrains out of plane movement of one atom in a 4 atom
 assembly (3 atoms centered around a fourth).
 Three atoms i,j,k define a plane and the motion of atom l out of this plane
 is restrained in order to insure that chirality and planarity within a
 protein.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The sinusodial term in the bonded potentials shown above is the proper dihedral
 angle which is used to describe the rotation around a chemical bond.
 In case of the proper dihedral angles, ethane is often used as an example
 how changes of the rotation around an angle lead to different energies
 (Ethane goes through 3 maximum and 3 minimum energy configurations during
 one rotation).
 Again 4 atoms (connected sequentially) are used in order to define 2 planes
 using the atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k,l$
\end_inset

 and then a cosine series expansion is applied to calculate the energy at
 different angles of those planes towards each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Non-bonded
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-bonded part of the potential energy function has two components:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{non-bonded} & = & V_{vdw}+V_{coulomb}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The van-der-waals (vdw) interactions is usually modelled by the Lennard-Jones
 (LJ) 6-12 potential 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{vdw} & = & \sum\epsilon\left[\left(\frac{R_{min}}{r}\right)^{12}-2\left(\frac{R_{min}}{r}\right)^{6}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 being the distance between two atoms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 being the well depth and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{min}$
\end_inset

 being the minimum interaction distance) which describes the interplay between
 attractive and repulsive forces between non-bonded atoms.
 The attractive 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-6}$
\end_inset

 part of the vdw interactions arise from the induced dipoles due to fluctuation
 of the electron clouds around atoms and can by itself be described through
 the London forces.
 The repulsive part 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-12}$
\end_inset

 originates from the Pauli principle that forbids the overlap of fully occupied
 electronic shells.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Coulomb potential describes the interaction between different partial
 charges on two atoms as point charges.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{coulomb} & = & \sum\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}r}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(r being the distance between atom 1 and 2, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset


