\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 being the partial charges and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 as the dielectric constant) 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Since the non-bonded terms are pairwise interactions between every pair
 of atoms within the system, calculating those interactions is in theory
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(N^{2})$
\end_inset

 problem and thus computationally very expensive.
 Therefore, an additional separation is applied in which the calculation
 of non-bonded interactions are split up into short range and long range
 interactions.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Due to the short range nature of the vdw-interactions (which falls off after
 ~8 Å), the use of a cut off distance and neighbour lists can be used to
 define the short range area.
 In cut-off based approaches the calculation of pair wise interactions is
 carried out within a distance cut-off that allows sufficient precision
 while still being computational affordable.
 This can reduce the complexity of the calculations to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(N)$
\end_inset

.
 Neighbour lists methods further reduce the cost of calculation of short
 range interactions by creating a list of atoms within the cut-off distance
 of the current atom.
 For a given number of time-steps (e.g.
 10), the pair wise interactions are only calculated for the atoms within
 that list assuming that in this time-frame the atoms remain within the
 cut-off distance.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In contrast to the short range vdw interactions, the electrostatic potential
 dominates the inter-particle potential way past the limitations of cut-off
 distances (which considerably falls off only after ~30 Å).
 Besides the increased cost due to the long range of the electrostatic interacti
ons, the sum in the coulomb potential converges very slow for large numbers
 of atoms hence a different treatment for these long range interactions
 should to be applied.
 In order to treat long range electrostatic interactions the Ewald summation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ewald1921"

\end_inset

 was introduced.
 In the Ewald summation the slowly converging series of the Coulomb potential
 is replaced by two faster converging series one in the real space and one
 in the reciprocal space (due to the fact of dealing with a lattice problem).
 Since Ewald is applied in a lattice, one of the requirements of using the
 Ewald summation is the use of explicit periodicity since this method was
 developed to treat electrostatic energies in crystals.
 The reciprocal part of the sum unfortunately still scales with 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}$
\end_inset

 thus further improvement of the Ewald scheme using the Particle Mesh Ewald
 (PME)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Darden1993"

\end_inset

 is used to improve the performance of the reciprocal sum.
 The fast Fourier transformation used in PME reduce the scaling of the algorithm
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N\, log\,(N)$
\end_inset

.
 Using PME the 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}$
\end_inset

 scaling of the electrostatic interactions can be reduced to a 
\begin_inset Formula $N\, log\,(N)$
\end_inset

 scaling problem without the need of using a cut-off based approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Statistical mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As previously described, MD simulations supply us with information about
 the system at a microscopic level.
 In order to obtain further (macroscopic) observables from this microscopic
 information, statistical mechanics have to be used.
 Deducting macroscopic information from our simulations enables us to draw
 conclusions comparable to experimental observations, along with ensuring
 that the conditions under which the system is studied are comparable to
 experimental data.
 The macroscopic observables depend on the position and velocity of the
 particles within the system and the instantaneous value of any observable
 A is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $A\,\left(p^{N}(t),r\,^{N}(t)\right)$
\end_inset

 at a specific time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 In an experimental setup, macroscopic properties are usually measured as
 a time average of the system since the information of the position and
 velocity of each particle is not accessible.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A_{ave} & = & \underset{\tau\rightarrow\infty}{lim}\frac{1}{\tau}\int_{t=0}^{\tau}A\,\left(p^{N}(t),r\,^{N}(t)\right)dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 As the time of the measurement increases, the average value approaches
 its ¨true¨ value.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

One could argue that we could generate a trajectory of a macroscopic system
 and then calculate the desired macroscopic property at each time-step and
 average over the simulation time.
 However, due to the complexity of macroscopic system (usually not less
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{23}$
\end_inset

 atoms), the time evolution of a property A becomes too complex and Gibbs
 suggested to replace it by the ensemble average.
 An ensemble can be seen as a number of points in the phase space where
 each point resembles a microstate of our system and the point distribution
 is described by a probability density p(T).
 The Liouville's theorem dp/dt ensures that the individual changes in the
 phase space will in total cancel each other out.
 If dealing with an equlibrated system where the defining properties of
 the ensemble (i.e.
 number of particles, volume and temperature) are constant, the total number
 of microstates is constant as well.
 Therefore, while the system evolves in time, one microstate moves into
 another state, hence a microstate that was in a different state will fill
 up the gap to ensure Liouville's theorem.
 During MD simulation instead of propagating the system in time, a trajectory
 moving from microstate to microstate is created instead, sampling the phase
 space.
 With a long enough sampling process, the trajectory could sample every
 possible microstate (assuming an equal probability) of the ensemble.
 An ensemble that follows the mentioned properties is called ergodic.
 However, the time needed to sample every microstate of an ensemble is beyond
 measurement, thus the correspondence to the time average is evident and
 the ergodic hypothesis (time average = ensemble average) allows us to calculate
 the ensemble average
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle A\right\rangle  & = & \iint dp^{N}dr^{N}A\left(p^{N},r^{N}\right)\rho\left(r^{N},r^{N}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

in place of the time average.
 One way to increase the sampling of the phase space, propagation of multiple
 trajectories with different starting configurations and/or velocities of
 the same system is used.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The different ensembles used in simulation are the following: 
